1
00:00:01,480 --> 00:00:04,009
CHAPTER ONE

2
00:00:04,009 --> 00:00:10,620
Stupid and rich, clever and poor

3
00:00:10,620 --> 00:00:17,289
What can you say about a twenty-five-year-old
girl who died?

4
00:00:17,289 --> 00:00:21,740
You can say that she was beautiful and intelligent.

5
00:00:21,740 --> 00:00:27,539
She loved Mozart and Bach and the Beatles.

6
00:00:27,539 --> 00:00:29,250
And me.

7
00:00:29,250 --> 00:00:35,140
Once, when she told me that, I asked her who
came first.

8
00:00:35,140 --> 00:00:40,860
She answered, smiling, "Like in the ABC.'

9
00:00:40,860 --> 00:00:43,610
I smiled too.

10
00:00:43,610 --> 00:00:46,110
But now I wonder.

11
00:00:46,110 --> 00:00:49,090
Was she talking about my first name?

12
00:00:49,090 --> 00:00:54,660
If she was, I came last, behind Mozart.

13
00:00:54,660 --> 00:00:57,680
Or did she mean my last name?

14
00:00:57,680 --> 00:01:03,270
If she did, I came between Bach and the Beatles.

15
00:01:03,270 --> 00:01:06,950
But I still didn't come first.

16
00:01:06,950 --> 00:01:09,830
That worries me terribly now.

17
00:01:09,830 --> 00:01:15,570
You see, I always had to be Number One.

18
00:01:15,570 --> 00:01:20,160
Family pride, you see.

19
00:01:20,160 --> 00:01:28,170
In the autumn of my last year at Harvard University,
I studied a lot in the Radcliffe library.

20
00:01:28,170 --> 00:01:34,250
The library was quiet, nobody knew me there,
and they had the books that I needed for my

21
00:01:34,250 --> 00:01:36,490
studies.

22
00:01:36,490 --> 00:01:43,439
The day before an examination, I went over
to the library desk to ask for a book.

23
00:01:43,439 --> 00:01:46,460
Two girls were working there.

24
00:01:46,460 --> 00:01:49,259
One was tall and sporty.

25
00:01:49,259 --> 00:01:52,729
The other was quiet and wore glasses.

26
00:01:52,729 --> 00:01:58,009
I chose her, and asked for my book.

27
00:01:58,009 --> 00:02:01,409
She gave me an unfriendly look.

28
00:02:01,409 --> 00:02:04,090
'Don't you have a library at Harvard?'

29
00:02:04,090 --> 00:02:06,729
she asked.

30
00:02:06,729 --> 00:02:10,110
'Radcliffe let us use their library,' I answered.

31
00:02:10,110 --> 00:02:15,000
'Yes, Preppie, they do - but is it fair?

32
00:02:15,000 --> 00:02:17,550
Harvard has five million books.

33
00:02:17,550 --> 00:02:19,630
We have a few thousand.'

34
00:02:19,630 --> 00:02:22,610
Oh dear, I thought.

35
00:02:22,610 --> 00:02:25,980
A clever Radcliffe girl.

36
00:02:25,980 --> 00:02:29,500
I can usually make girls like her feel very
small.

37
00:02:29,500 --> 00:02:34,880
But I needed that damn book, so I had to be
polite.

38
00:02:34,880 --> 00:02:38,480
'Listen, I need that damn book.'

39
00:02:38,480 --> 00:02:42,239
'Don't speak like that to a lady, Preppie.'

40
00:02:42,239 --> 00:02:47,690
'Why are you so sure that I went to prep school?'

41
00:02:47,690 --> 00:02:50,110
She took off her glasses.

42
00:02:50,110 --> 00:02:53,959
'You look stupid and rich,' she said.

43
00:02:53,959 --> 00:02:56,980
'You're wrong,' I said.

44
00:02:56,980 --> 00:03:00,020
'I'm actually clever and poor.'

45
00:03:00,020 --> 00:03:04,500
'Oh no, Preppie,' she said.

46
00:03:04,500 --> 00:03:08,730
'I'm clever and poor.'

47
00:03:08,730 --> 00:03:11,310
She was looking straight at me.

48
00:03:11,310 --> 00:03:19,780
All right, she had pretty brown eyes; and
OK, perhaps I looked rich.

49
00:03:19,780 --> 00:03:23,310
But I don't let anyone call me stupid.

50
00:03:23,310 --> 00:03:25,980
'What makes you so clever?'

51
00:03:25,980 --> 00:03:26,980
I asked.

52
00:03:26,980 --> 00:03:32,110
'I'm not going to go for coffee with you,'
she said.

53
00:03:32,110 --> 00:03:34,860
'Listen - I'm not going to ask you!'

54
00:03:34,860 --> 00:03:40,400
'That', she said, 'is what makes you stupid.'

55
00:03:40,400 --> 00:03:43,930
Let me explain why I took her for coffee.

56
00:03:43,930 --> 00:03:47,239
I got the book that I wanted, didn't I?

57
00:03:47,239 --> 00:03:51,069
And she couldn't leave the library until closing
time.

58
00:03:51,069 --> 00:03:55,480
So I was able to study the book for a good
long time.

59
00:03:55,480 --> 00:03:58,630
I got an A in my exam the next day.

60
00:03:58,630 --> 00:04:06,780
I gave the girl's legs an A too, when she
came out from behind the library desk.

61
00:04:06,780 --> 00:04:11,349
We went to a coffee shop and I ordered coffee
for both of us.

62
00:04:11,349 --> 00:04:14,730
'I'm Jennifer Cavilleri,' she said.

63
00:04:14,730 --> 00:04:18,829
'I'm American, but my family came from Italy.

64
00:04:18,829 --> 00:04:19,829
I'm studying music'

65
00:04:19,829 --> 00:04:23,360
'My name is Oliver,' I said.

66
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:26,759
'Is that you're first or your last name?'

67
00:04:26,759 --> 00:04:28,310
she asked.

68
00:04:28,310 --> 00:04:29,860
'First.

69
00:04:29,860 --> 00:04:32,090
My other name is Barrett.'

70
00:04:32,090 --> 00:04:33,810
'Oh,' she said.

71
00:04:33,810 --> 00:04:36,910
'Like Elizabeth Barrett the writer?'

72
00:04:36,910 --> 00:04:39,289
'Yes,' I said.

73
00:04:39,289 --> 00:04:41,530
'No relation.'

74
00:04:41,530 --> 00:04:48,310
I was pleased that she hadn't said, 'Barrett,
like Barrett Hall?'

75
00:04:48,310 --> 00:04:52,160
That Barrett is a relation of mine.

76
00:04:52,160 --> 00:04:57,660
Barrett Hall is a large, unlovely building
at Harvard University.

77
00:04:57,660 --> 00:05:05,360
My great grandfather gave it to Harvard long
ago, and I am deeply ashamed of it.

78
00:05:05,360 --> 00:05:07,230
She was silent.

79
00:05:07,230 --> 00:05:10,920
She sat there, half-smiling at me.

80
00:05:10,920 --> 00:05:13,000
I looked at her notebooks.

81
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:15,830
'Sixteenth-century music?'

82
00:05:15,830 --> 00:05:16,830
I said.

83
00:05:16,830 --> 00:05:19,520
'That sounds difficult.'

84
00:05:19,520 --> 00:05:23,700
'It's too difficult for you, Preppie,' she
said coldly.

85
00:05:23,700 --> 00:05:28,220
Why was I letting her talk to me like this?

86
00:05:28,220 --> 00:05:31,870
Didn't she read the university magazine?

87
00:05:31,870 --> 00:05:34,410
Didn't she know who I was?

88
00:05:34,410 --> 00:05:38,150
'Hey, don't you know who I am?'

89
00:05:38,150 --> 00:05:40,150
'Yes,' she answered.

90
00:05:40,150 --> 00:05:44,280
'You're the man who owns Barrett Hall.'

91
00:05:44,280 --> 00:05:46,600
She didn't know who I was.

92
00:05:46,600 --> 00:05:50,880
'I don't own Barrett Hall,' I argued.

93
00:05:50,880 --> 00:05:55,419
'My great-grandfather gave it to Harvard,
that's all.'

94
00:05:55,419 --> 00:06:02,949
'So that's why his not-so-great grandson could
get into Harvard so easily!'

95
00:06:02,949 --> 00:06:05,100
I was angry now.

96
00:06:05,100 --> 00:06:11,690
'Jenny, if I'm no good, why did you want me
to invite you for coffee?'

97
00:06:11,690 --> 00:06:15,590
She looked straight into my eyes and smiled.

98
00:06:15,590 --> 00:06:18,090
'I like your body!'

99
00:06:18,090 --> 00:06:21,410
she said.

100
00:06:21,410 --> 00:06:25,919
Every big winner has to be a good loser too.

101
00:06:25,919 --> 00:06:28,960
Every good Harvard man knows that.

102
00:06:28,960 --> 00:06:31,940
But it's better if you can win.

103
00:06:31,940 --> 00:06:38,750
And so, as I walked with Jenny to her dormitory,
I made my winning move.

104
00:06:38,750 --> 00:06:43,770
'Listen, Friday night is the Dartmouth hockey
match?

105
00:06:43,770 --> 00:06:44,770
'So?'

106
00:06:44,770 --> 00:06:47,819
'So I'd like you to come.'

107
00:06:47,819 --> 00:06:51,740
These Radcliffe girls, they really care about
sport.

108
00:06:51,740 --> 00:06:57,740
'And why', she asked, 'should I come to a
stupid ice-hockey match?'

109
00:06:57,740 --> 00:07:01,030
'Because I'm playing,' I answered.

110
00:07:01,030 --> 00:07:03,919
There was a moment's silence.

111
00:07:03,919 --> 00:07:07,259
I think I heard snow falling.

112
00:07:07,259 --> 00:07:09,680
'For which team?'

113
00:07:09,680 --> 00:07:13,729
she said.

114
00:07:13,729 --> 00:07:20,569
By the second quarter of the game on Friday
night, we were winning 0:0.

115
00:07:20,569 --> 00:07:26,120
That is, Davey Johnson and I were getting
ready to score a goal.

116
00:07:26,120 --> 00:07:31,500
The crowd were screaming for blood - or a
goal.

117
00:07:31,500 --> 00:07:36,370
I always feel that it's my job to give them
both these things.

118
00:07:36,370 --> 00:07:42,240
I didn't look up at Jenny once, but I hoped
she was watching me.

119
00:07:42,240 --> 00:07:46,590
I got the puck and started off across the
ice.

120
00:07:46,590 --> 00:07:52,250
Davey Johnson was there on my left, but I
didn't pass the puck to him.

121
00:07:52,250 --> 00:07:56,180
I wanted to score this goal myself.

122
00:07:56,180 --> 00:08:01,650
But before I could shoot, two big Dartmouth
men were after me.

123
00:08:01,650 --> 00:08:07,440
In a moment, we were hitting the puck and
each other as hard as we could.

124
00:08:07,440 --> 00:08:10,139
'You!' said a voice suddenly.

125
00:08:10,139 --> 00:08:14,080
'Two minutes in the penalty box.'

126
00:08:14,080 --> 00:08:15,620
I looked up.

127
00:08:15,620 --> 00:08:17,780
He was talking to me.

128
00:08:17,780 --> 00:08:20,800
'What did I do?'

129
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:22,070
I asked.

130
00:08:22,070 --> 00:08:23,330
'Don't argue.'

131
00:08:23,330 --> 00:08:30,370
He called to the officials' desk: 'Number
seven, two minutes in the penalty box, for

132
00:08:30,370 --> 00:08:31,770
fighting.'

133
00:08:31,770 --> 00:08:36,260
Angrily I climbed into the penalty box.

134
00:08:36,260 --> 00:08:42,120
'Why are you sitting here when all your friends
are playing?'

135
00:08:42,120 --> 00:08:44,300
The voice was Jenny's.

136
00:08:44,300 --> 00:08:45,830
I didn't answer.

137
00:08:45,830 --> 00:08:49,360
'Come on, Harvard, get that puck!'

138
00:08:49,360 --> 00:08:50,959
I shouted.

139
00:08:50,959 --> 00:08:53,580
'What did you do wrong?'

140
00:08:53,580 --> 00:08:54,770
Jenny asked.

141
00:08:54,770 --> 00:08:57,860
'I tried too hard.'

142
00:08:57,860 --> 00:09:03,640
Out there on the ice Harvard were playing
with only five men.

143
00:09:03,640 --> 00:09:06,070
'Is that something to be ashamed of?'

144
00:09:06,070 --> 00:09:07,820
'Jenny, please.

145
00:09:07,820 --> 00:09:09,070
I'm thinking.'

146
00:09:09,070 --> 00:09:11,570
'What about?'

147
00:09:11,570 --> 00:09:14,010
'About those two Dartmouth men.

148
00:09:14,010 --> 00:09:18,459
When I get back onto the ice, I'll break them
into little pieces.'

149
00:09:18,459 --> 00:09:23,420
'Do you always fight when you play hockey?'

150
00:09:23,420 --> 00:09:26,340
'I'll fight you, Jenny, if you don't keep
quiet.'

151
00:09:26,340 --> 00:09:28,930
'I'm leaving.

152
00:09:28,930 --> 00:09:30,220
Goodbye.'

153
00:09:30,220 --> 00:09:35,440
I looked round, but she had gone.

154
00:09:35,440 --> 00:09:37,480
Just then, the bell rang.

155
00:09:37,480 --> 00:09:40,930
My two-minute penalty had finished.

156
00:09:40,930 --> 00:09:43,220
I jumped onto the ice again.

157
00:09:43,220 --> 00:09:45,970
'Good old Barrett!'

158
00:09:45,970 --> 00:09:49,029
shouted the crowd.

159
00:09:49,029 --> 00:09:51,740
Jenny will hear them shouting for me, I thought.

160
00:09:51,740 --> 00:09:54,480
But where was she?

161
00:09:54,480 --> 00:09:56,950
Had she left?

162
00:09:56,950 --> 00:10:01,840
As I went for the puck, I looked up into the
crowd.

163
00:10:01,840 --> 00:10:04,339
Jenny was standing there.

164
00:10:04,339 --> 00:10:08,420
I took the puck and went towards the goal
line.

165
00:10:08,420 --> 00:10:11,700
Two Dartmouth players were coming straight
at me.

166
00:10:11,700 --> 00:10:14,190
'Go, Oliver, go!

167
00:10:14,190 --> 00:10:17,500
Knock their heads off!'

168
00:10:17,500 --> 00:10:20,350
That was Jenny's voice above the crowd.

169
00:10:20,350 --> 00:10:24,570
It was crazily, beautifully violent.

170
00:10:24,570 --> 00:10:27,820
I pushed past one Dartmouth man.

171
00:10:27,820 --> 00:10:31,240
I knocked hard into the other.

172
00:10:31,240 --> 00:10:37,529
Then I passed the puck to Davey Johnson, and
he banged it into the Dartmouth goal.

173
00:10:37,529 --> 00:10:41,260
The crowd went wild.

174
00:10:41,260 --> 00:10:47,490
In a moment we were all shouting and kissing
and banging each other on the back.

175
00:10:47,490 --> 00:10:51,530
The crowd were screaming with excitement.

176
00:10:51,530 --> 00:11:00,320
After that, we murdered Dartmouth - seven
goals to zero.

177
00:11:00,320 --> 00:11:06,750
After the match, I lay in the hot bath and
thought with pride about the game.

178
00:11:06,750 --> 00:11:11,800
I'd scored one goal, and helped to score another.

179
00:11:11,800 --> 00:11:17,950
Now the water felt wonderful on my tired body.

180
00:11:17,950 --> 00:11:20,360
Ahhhh!

181
00:11:20,360 --> 00:11:23,519
Suddenly I remembered Jenny.

182
00:11:23,519 --> 00:11:26,139
Was she still waiting outside?

183
00:11:26,139 --> 00:11:27,500
I hoped so!

184
00:11:27,500 --> 00:11:32,769
I jumped out of that bath and dressed as fast
as I could.

185
00:11:32,769 --> 00:11:37,500
Outside, the cold winter air hit me.

186
00:11:37,500 --> 00:11:40,190
I looked round for Jenny.

187
00:11:40,190 --> 00:11:44,170
Had she walked back to her dormitory alone?

188
00:11:44,170 --> 00:11:46,370
Suddenly I saw her.

189
00:11:46,370 --> 00:11:50,670
'Hey, Preppie, it's cold out here.'

190
00:11:50,670 --> 00:11:55,130
I was really pleased to see her, and gave
her a quick kiss.

191
00:11:55,130 --> 00:11:58,390
'Did I say you could kiss me?'

192
00:11:58,390 --> 00:11:59,390
she said.

193
00:11:59,390 --> 00:12:00,390
'Sorry.

194
00:12:00,390 --> 00:12:03,339
I was just excited.'

195
00:12:03,339 --> 00:12:05,839
'I wasn't.'

196
00:12:05,839 --> 00:12:10,510
It was dark and quiet, out there in the cold.

197
00:12:10,510 --> 00:12:15,640
I kissed her again, more slowly.

198
00:12:15,640 --> 00:12:20,720
When we reached her dormitory, I did not kiss
her goodnight.

199
00:12:20,720 --> 00:12:28,120
'Listen, Jenny, perhaps I won't telephone
you for a few months.'

200
00:12:28,120 --> 00:12:30,760
She was silent for a moment.

201
00:12:30,760 --> 00:12:32,090
'Why?'

202
00:12:32,090 --> 00:12:34,330
she asked at last.

203
00:12:34,330 --> 00:12:40,560
'But perhaps I'll telephone you as soon as
I get back to my dorm.'

204
00:12:40,560 --> 00:12:44,140
I turned and began to walk away.

205
00:12:44,140 --> 00:12:46,440
'Damn Preppie!'

206
00:12:46,440 --> 00:12:48,050
I heard her say.

207
00:12:48,050 --> 00:12:50,870
I turned again.

208
00:12:50,870 --> 00:12:55,649
From twenty feet away I scored another goal.

209
00:12:55,649 --> 00:13:01,990
'You see, Jenny, that's the kind of thing
you say.

210
00:13:01,990 --> 00:13:07,070
And when other people do it to you, you don't
like it.'

211
00:13:07,070 --> 00:13:10,430
I wished I could see the look on her face.

212
00:13:10,430 --> 00:13:12,579
But I couldn't look back.

213
00:13:12,579 --> 00:13:17,899
My pride wouldn't let me.

214
00:13:17,899 --> 00:13:22,610
When I returned to my dorm, Ray Stratton was
there.

215
00:13:22,610 --> 00:13:25,560
He and I slept in the same room.

216
00:13:25,560 --> 00:13:30,180
Ray was playing cards with some of his football-playing
friends.

217
00:13:30,180 --> 00:13:33,030
'Hello, Ollie,' said Ray.

218
00:13:33,030 --> 00:13:35,430
'How many goals did you score?'

219
00:13:35,430 --> 00:13:40,570
'I scored one, and I made one,' I answered.

220
00:13:40,570 --> 00:13:42,130
'With Cavilleri?'

221
00:13:42,130 --> 00:13:44,079
'That's none of your business!'

222
00:13:44,079 --> 00:13:45,920
I replied quickly.

223
00:13:45,920 --> 00:13:48,130
'Who's Cavilleri?'

224
00:13:48,130 --> 00:13:50,310
asked one of the footballers.

225
00:13:50,310 --> 00:13:52,130
'Jenny Cavilleri.

226
00:13:52,130 --> 00:13:53,380
Studies music.

227
00:13:53,380 --> 00:13:55,320
Plays the piano with the Music Group.'

228
00:13:55,320 --> 00:13:59,580
'What does she play with Barrett?'

229
00:13:59,580 --> 00:14:00,870
Everyone laughed.

230
00:14:00,870 --> 00:14:02,529
'Get lost!'

231
00:14:02,529 --> 00:14:07,089
I said as I entered my room.

232
00:14:07,089 --> 00:14:13,589
There I took off my shoes, lay back on my
bed and telephoned Jenny's dormitory.

233
00:14:13,589 --> 00:14:16,199
'Hey, Jen...'

234
00:14:16,199 --> 00:14:18,380
I said softly.

235
00:14:18,380 --> 00:14:19,610
'Yes?'

236
00:14:19,610 --> 00:14:24,930
'I think I'm in love with you.'

237
00:14:24,930 --> 00:14:27,940
She was silent for a few moments.

238
00:14:27,940 --> 00:14:36,070
Then she answered, very softly: 'Oliver, you're
crazy.'

239
00:14:36,070 --> 00:14:38,660
I wasn't unhappy.

240
00:14:38,660 --> 00:14:44,420
Or surprised.

241
00:14:44,420 --> 00:14:47,000
CHAPTER TWO

242
00:14:47,000 --> 00:14:51,360
Blood and stone

243
00:14:51,360 --> 00:14:57,199
A few weeks later, I was hurt in the hockey
match at Cornell University.

244
00:14:57,199 --> 00:15:04,149
My face was badly cut and the officials gave
me the penalty for starting the fight.

245
00:15:04,149 --> 00:15:06,710
Five minutes!

246
00:15:06,710 --> 00:15:13,620
I sat quietly in the penalty box while the
team manager cleaned the blood off my face.

247
00:15:13,620 --> 00:15:17,149
I was ashamed to look out onto the ice.

248
00:15:17,149 --> 00:15:21,209
But the shouts of the crowd told me everything.

249
00:15:21,209 --> 00:15:24,230
Cornell scored a goal.

250
00:15:24,230 --> 00:15:27,040
The score was 3-3 now.

251
00:15:27,040 --> 00:15:29,949
Damn, I thought.

252
00:15:29,949 --> 00:15:35,699
We're going to lose this match, because of
me.

253
00:15:35,699 --> 00:15:40,889
Across the ice, among the crowd, I saw him.

254
00:15:40,889 --> 00:15:43,220
My father.

255
00:15:43,220 --> 00:15:46,079
Old Stony face.

256
00:15:46,079 --> 00:15:49,029
He was looking straight at me.

257
00:15:49,029 --> 00:15:57,110
'If the meeting finishes in time, I'll come
to Cornell and watch you play,' he had told

258
00:15:57,110 --> 00:15:59,880
me on the phone.

259
00:15:59,880 --> 00:16:04,810
And there he was, Oliver Barrett the Third.

260
00:16:04,810 --> 00:16:08,769
What was he thinking about?

261
00:16:08,769 --> 00:16:10,120
Who could say?

262
00:16:10,120 --> 00:16:13,620
Why was he here?

263
00:16:13,620 --> 00:16:15,930
Family pride, perhaps.

264
00:16:15,930 --> 00:16:17,779
'Look at me.

265
00:16:17,779 --> 00:16:25,250
I am a very busy, important man, but I have
come all the way to Cornell, just to watch

266
00:16:25,250 --> 00:16:30,800
my son play in a hockey match.'

267
00:16:30,800 --> 00:16:35,170
We lost six goals to three.

268
00:16:35,170 --> 00:16:40,889
After the match the doctor put twelve stitches
in my face.

269
00:16:40,889 --> 00:16:44,389
When I got to the changing-room, it was empty.

270
00:16:44,389 --> 00:16:47,889
They don't want to talk to me, I thought.

271
00:16:47,889 --> 00:16:50,870
I lost that match.

272
00:16:50,870 --> 00:16:55,190
I felt very ashamed as I walked out into the
winter night.

273
00:16:55,190 --> 00:17:00,699
'Come and have dinner, son,' said a voice.

274
00:17:00,699 --> 00:17:03,380
It was Old Stony face.

275
00:17:03,380 --> 00:17:09,799
At dinner, we had one of our non-conversations.

276
00:17:09,799 --> 00:17:15,209
We spoke to each other, but didn't actually
say anything.

277
00:17:15,209 --> 00:17:22,450
These non-conversations always started with
'How have you been, son?' and ended with 'Is

278
00:17:22,450 --> 00:17:25,520
there anything I can do for you?'

279
00:17:25,520 --> 00:17:28,660
'How have you been, son?'

280
00:17:28,660 --> 00:17:30,200
my father began.

281
00:17:30,200 --> 00:17:32,160
'Fine, sir.'

282
00:17:32,160 --> 00:17:33,740
'Does your face hurt?'

283
00:17:33,740 --> 00:17:35,669
'No, sir.'

284
00:17:35,669 --> 00:17:38,570
(It hurt terribly.)

285
00:17:38,570 --> 00:17:43,520
Next, Old Stony face talked about Playing
the Game.

286
00:17:43,520 --> 00:17:48,289
'All right, son, you lost the match.'

287
00:17:48,289 --> 00:17:52,370
(How clever of you to notice, Father.)

288
00:17:52,370 --> 00:18:00,290
'But after all, in sport, the important thing
is the playing, not the winning.'

289
00:18:00,290 --> 00:18:03,120
Wonderful, I thought.

290
00:18:03,120 --> 00:18:06,540
Father was chosen for the Olympic Games.

291
00:18:06,540 --> 00:18:11,650
And now he says winning is not important!

292
00:18:11,650 --> 00:18:18,870
I just looked down at my plate and said 'Yes,
sir, at the right times.'

293
00:18:18,870 --> 00:18:22,150
Our non-conversation continued.

294
00:18:22,150 --> 00:18:27,100
After playing the game, he discussed My Plans.

295
00:18:27,100 --> 00:18:33,830
'Tell me, Oliver, has the Law School accepted
you yet?'

296
00:18:33,830 --> 00:18:35,240
'Not yet, sir.'

297
00:18:35,240 --> 00:18:38,800
'Would you like me to telephone them?'

298
00:18:38,800 --> 00:18:39,800
'No!'

299
00:18:39,800 --> 00:18:41,260
I said at once.

300
00:18:41,260 --> 00:18:45,560
'I want to get a letter like other people,
sir.

301
00:18:45,560 --> 00:18:46,740
Please.'

302
00:18:46,740 --> 00:18:49,510
'Yes, of course.

303
00:18:49,510 --> 00:18:51,040
Fine...

304
00:18:51,040 --> 00:18:54,549
After all, they're sure to accept you."

305
00:18:54,549 --> 00:18:55,679
Why?

306
00:18:55,679 --> 00:18:57,929
I thought.

307
00:18:57,929 --> 00:19:00,950
Because I'm clever and successful?

308
00:19:00,950 --> 00:19:06,590
Or because I'm the son of Oliver Barrett the
Third?

309
00:19:06,590 --> 00:19:11,020
The meal was as uninteresting as the conversation.

310
00:19:11,020 --> 00:19:14,299
At last, my father spoke again.

311
00:19:14,299 --> 00:19:19,010
'There's always the Peace Corps,' he said
suddenly.

312
00:19:19,010 --> 00:19:24,570
'I think the Peace Corps is a fine thing,
don't you?'

313
00:19:24,570 --> 00:19:28,490
'Oh, yes, sir,' I said politely.

314
00:19:28,490 --> 00:19:31,380
I knew nothing about the Peace Corps.

315
00:19:31,380 --> 00:19:36,770
'What do your friends at Harvard think about
the Peace Corps?' he asked.

316
00:19:36,770 --> 00:19:42,510
'Do they feel that the Peace Corps is important
in our world today?'

317
00:19:42,510 --> 00:19:49,070
'Yes, sir,' I said politely, just to please
him.

318
00:19:49,070 --> 00:19:52,110
After dinner, I walked with him to his car.

319
00:19:52,110 --> 00:19:58,120
'Is there anything I can do for you, son?'
he asked.

320
00:19:58,120 --> 00:20:00,950
'No, thank you, sir.

321
00:20:00,950 --> 00:20:03,080
Good night, sir.'

322
00:20:03,080 --> 00:20:08,580
Our non-conversation was finished: he drove
away.

323
00:20:08,580 --> 00:20:16,740
Yes, of course there are planes, but Oliver
Barrett the Third chose to drive.

324
00:20:16,740 --> 00:20:21,150
My father likes to drive - fast.

325
00:20:21,150 --> 00:20:30,780
And at that time of night, in an Aston Martin
DBS, you can go very fast indeed.

326
00:20:30,780 --> 00:20:33,580
I went to telephone Jenny.

327
00:20:33,580 --> 00:20:36,700
That was the only good part of the evening.

328
00:20:36,700 --> 00:20:39,390
I told her about the fight.

329
00:20:39,390 --> 00:20:41,390
She enjoyed that.

330
00:20:41,390 --> 00:20:45,150
Her musical friends never got into fights.

331
00:20:45,150 --> 00:20:49,799
'I hope you hit the man who hit you,' she
said.

332
00:20:49,799 --> 00:20:51,480
'Oh, yes.'

333
00:20:51,480 --> 00:20:52,480
'Good!

334
00:20:52,480 --> 00:20:55,870
I'm sorry I couldn't be there to watch you.

335
00:20:55,870 --> 00:20:58,680
Perhaps you'll hit somebody in the Yale match?'

336
00:20:58,680 --> 00:21:01,049
I smiled.

337
00:21:01,049 --> 00:21:05,900
Jenny really made me feel better.

338
00:21:05,900 --> 00:21:10,330
Back at Harvard the next day, I called at
her dorm.

339
00:21:10,330 --> 00:21:13,510
Jenny was talking to someone on the telephone
in the hall.

340
00:21:13,510 --> 00:21:14,510
'Yes.

341
00:21:14,510 --> 00:21:15,510
Of course!

342
00:21:15,510 --> 00:21:17,460
Oh yes, Phil.

343
00:21:17,460 --> 00:21:20,500
I love you too.

344
00:21:20,500 --> 00:21:22,570
Love and kisses.

345
00:21:22,570 --> 00:21:23,570
Goodbye.'

346
00:21:23,570 --> 00:21:26,120
Who was she talking to?

347
00:21:26,120 --> 00:21:34,429
I had only been away forty-eight hours, and
she had found a new boyfriend!

348
00:21:34,429 --> 00:21:36,980
Jenny did not seem ashamed.

349
00:21:36,980 --> 00:21:40,279
She kissed me lightly on the unhurt side of
my face.

350
00:21:40,279 --> 00:21:43,240
'Hey - you look terrible!'

351
00:21:43,240 --> 00:21:45,470
'Twelve stitches, Jen.'

352
00:21:45,470 --> 00:21:48,970
'Does the other man look worse than you?'

353
00:21:48,970 --> 00:21:50,520
'Much worse.

354
00:21:50,520 --> 00:21:54,159
I always make the other man look worse.'

355
00:21:54,159 --> 00:21:56,890
We walked to my MG sports car.

356
00:21:56,890 --> 00:21:58,600
'Who's Phil?'

357
00:21:58,600 --> 00:22:01,700
I asked as carelessly as I could.

358
00:22:01,700 --> 00:22:04,030
'My father.'

359
00:22:04,030 --> 00:22:07,070
I could not believe that!

360
00:22:07,070 --> 00:22:08,980
'You call your father Phil?'

361
00:22:08,980 --> 00:22:10,260
'That's his name.

362
00:22:10,260 --> 00:22:13,830
What do you call your father?'

363
00:22:13,830 --> 00:22:15,429
'Sir.'

364
00:22:15,429 --> 00:22:18,039
'He must be really proud of you.

365
00:22:18,039 --> 00:22:23,640
You're a big hockey star - and you're always
successful in your exams.'

366
00:22:23,640 --> 00:22:26,750
'You don't know anything, Jenny.

367
00:22:26,750 --> 00:22:30,290
He was good at exams and sport, too.

368
00:22:30,290 --> 00:22:32,029
He was in the Olympic Games.'

369
00:22:32,029 --> 00:22:33,799
'My God!

370
00:22:33,799 --> 00:22:36,169
Did he win?'

371
00:22:36,169 --> 00:22:37,659
'No.'

372
00:22:37,659 --> 00:22:45,570
(Actually, Old Stony face was sixth, which
makes me feel a little better.)

373
00:22:45,570 --> 00:22:47,510
Jenny was silent for a moment.

374
00:22:47,510 --> 00:22:51,090
'Why do you hate him so much?'

375
00:22:51,090 --> 00:22:54,320
she asked at last.

376
00:22:54,320 --> 00:22:58,529
'I'm Oliver Barrett the Fourth,' I answered.

377
00:22:58,529 --> 00:23:01,890
'All Barrett's have to be successful.

378
00:23:01,890 --> 00:23:07,070
And that means I have to be good at everything,
all the time.

379
00:23:07,070 --> 00:23:09,340
I hate it.'

380
00:23:09,340 --> 00:23:13,029
'Oh, I'm sure you do,' laughed Jenny.

381
00:23:13,029 --> 00:23:15,840
'You hate doing well in your exams.

382
00:23:15,840 --> 00:23:18,190
You hate being a hockey star...'

383
00:23:18,190 --> 00:23:20,200
'But he expects it!'

384
00:23:20,200 --> 00:23:21,210
I said.

385
00:23:21,210 --> 00:23:26,659
'If I'm successful, he isn't excited, or surprised.

386
00:23:26,659 --> 00:23:32,120
He was a big success, and he expects me to
be the same.'

387
00:23:32,120 --> 00:23:40,610
I told her about our meal and our non-conversation
after the Cornell match, but she didn't understand

388
00:23:40,610 --> 00:23:43,110
at all.

389
00:23:43,110 --> 00:23:47,289
'You say your father is a busy man,' she said.

390
00:23:47,289 --> 00:23:52,659
'But he found time to go all the way to Cornell
to watch you play.

391
00:23:52,659 --> 00:23:58,669
How can you say these terrible things about
him, when he drove all that way, just to watch

392
00:23:58,669 --> 00:24:00,400
your hockey match?

393
00:24:00,400 --> 00:24:04,620
He loves you, Oliver - can't you understand?'

394
00:24:04,620 --> 00:24:09,809
'Forget it, Jenny,' I said.

395
00:24:09,809 --> 00:24:13,700
She was silent for a moment.

396
00:24:13,700 --> 00:24:18,730
'I'm pleased you have problems with your father,'
she said at last.

397
00:24:18,730 --> 00:24:21,159
'That means you aren't perfect.'

398
00:24:21,159 --> 00:24:26,400
'Oh - you mean you are perfect?'

399
00:24:26,400 --> 00:24:28,620
'Of course not, Preppie.

400
00:24:28,620 --> 00:24:32,130
That's why I go out with you!'

401
00:24:32,130 --> 00:24:38,980
Jenny loved to have the last word.

402
00:24:38,980 --> 00:24:41,360
CHAPTER THREE

403
00:24:41,360 --> 00:24:45,950
We belong together

404
00:24:45,950 --> 00:24:49,270
I had not yet made love to Jenny.

405
00:24:49,270 --> 00:24:53,960
In the three weeks we had been together, we
had held hands.

406
00:24:53,960 --> 00:24:58,809
Sometimes we had kissed, but that was all.

407
00:24:58,809 --> 00:25:04,210
Usually I moved much faster - ask the other
girls that I'd been out with!

408
00:25:04,210 --> 00:25:07,770
But Jenny was special.

409
00:25:07,770 --> 00:25:13,840
I felt different about her and I didn't know
what to say to her.

410
00:25:13,840 --> 00:25:17,529
'You're going to fail your exams, Oliver.'

411
00:25:17,529 --> 00:25:21,789
We were studying in my room one Sunday afternoon.

412
00:25:21,789 --> 00:25:26,760
'Oliver, you'll fail your exams if you don't
do some work.'

413
00:25:26,760 --> 00:25:28,990
'I am working.'

414
00:25:28,990 --> 00:25:31,130
'No, you aren't.

415
00:25:31,130 --> 00:25:33,380
You're looking at my legs.'

416
00:25:33,380 --> 00:25:35,580
'Only once every chapter.'

417
00:25:35,580 --> 00:25:38,200
'That book has very short chapters.'

418
00:25:38,200 --> 00:25:42,240
'Listen, you aren't as good-looking as all
that!'

419
00:25:42,240 --> 00:25:46,919
'I know, but you think I am, don't you?'

420
00:25:46,919 --> 00:25:53,929
'Dammit, Jenny, how can I study when all the
time I want to make love to you?'

421
00:25:53,929 --> 00:25:58,320
She closed her book softly and put it down.

422
00:25:58,320 --> 00:26:00,780
She put her arms around me.

423
00:26:00,780 --> 00:26:06,110
'Oliver, will you please make love to me?'

424
00:26:06,110 --> 00:26:10,350
It all happened at once.

425
00:26:10,350 --> 00:26:17,330
It was all so unhurried, soft and gentle.

426
00:26:17,330 --> 00:26:19,669
And I was gentle too.

427
00:26:19,669 --> 00:26:23,550
Was this the real Oliver Barrett the Fourth?

428
00:26:23,550 --> 00:26:33,020
'Hey, Oliver, did I ever tell you that I love
you?' said Jenny finally.

429
00:26:33,020 --> 00:26:35,340
'No, Jen.'

430
00:26:35,340 --> 00:26:38,060
I kissed her neck.

431
00:26:38,060 --> 00:26:43,880
'I love you very much, Oliver.'

432
00:26:43,880 --> 00:26:46,399
I love Ray Stratton too.

433
00:26:46,399 --> 00:26:55,539
He's not very clever, or a wonderful footballer,
but he was a good friend to me.

434
00:26:55,539 --> 00:26:58,990
Where did he go to study when I was in our
room with Jenny?

435
00:26:58,990 --> 00:27:05,929
Where did he sleep on those Saturdays when
Jenny and I spent the night together?

436
00:27:05,929 --> 00:27:10,760
In the old days, I always told him all about
my girlfriends.

437
00:27:10,760 --> 00:27:13,620
But I never told him about Jenny and me.

438
00:27:13,620 --> 00:27:20,180
'My God, Barrett, are you two sleeping together
or not?' asked Ray.

439
00:27:20,180 --> 00:27:23,350
'Raymond, please don't ask.'

440
00:27:23,350 --> 00:27:26,600
'You spend every minute of your free time
with her.

441
00:27:26,600 --> 00:27:28,570
It isn't natural...'

442
00:27:28,570 --> 00:27:32,020
'Ray, when two adults are in love...'

443
00:27:32,020 --> 00:27:33,020
'Love?

444
00:27:33,020 --> 00:27:34,020
At your age?

445
00:27:34,020 --> 00:27:37,779
My God, I worry about you, I really do.'

446
00:27:37,779 --> 00:27:40,809
'Don't worry, Raymond, old friend.

447
00:27:40,809 --> 00:27:44,860
We'll have that flat in New York one day.

448
00:27:44,860 --> 00:27:46,529
Different girls every night...'

449
00:27:46,529 --> 00:27:50,060
'Don't you tell me not to worry, Barrett.

450
00:27:50,060 --> 00:27:55,690
That girl's got you, and I don't like it!'

451
00:27:55,690 --> 00:28:00,350
That evening I went to hear Jenny play the
piano with the Music Group.

452
00:28:00,350 --> 00:28:04,910
'You were wonderful,' I said afterwards.

453
00:28:04,910 --> 00:28:10,240
'That shows what you know about music, Preppie.'

454
00:28:10,240 --> 00:28:12,320
We walked along the river together.

455
00:28:12,320 --> 00:28:14,850
'I played OK.

456
00:28:14,850 --> 00:28:16,320
Not wonderful.

457
00:28:16,320 --> 00:28:18,890
Not "Olympic Games".

458
00:28:18,890 --> 00:28:20,190
Just OK.

459
00:28:20,190 --> 00:28:21,370
OK?'

460
00:28:21,370 --> 00:28:26,769
'OK - but you should always continue your
music'

461
00:28:26,769 --> 00:28:27,769
'Of course I will.

462
00:28:27,769 --> 00:28:33,150
I'm going to study with Nadia Boulanger, aren't
